B-tree indexes only support left-anchored pattern matching. A leading wildcard forces a full table scan.

```sql
-- This uses the B-tree index
SELECT * FROM users WHERE name LIKE 'John%';

-- This does NOT use the B-tree index (leading wildcard)
SELECT * FROM users WHERE name LIKE '%John%';

-- Fix 1: Use pg_trgm GIN index for substring matching
CREATE EXTENSION IF NOT EXISTS pg_trgm;
CREATE INDEX idx_users_name_trgm ON users USING gin (name gin_trgm_ops);

-- Now this uses the trigram index
SELECT * FROM users WHERE name LIKE '%John%';
SELECT * FROM users WHERE name ILIKE '%john%';  -- case-insensitive too

-- Fix 2: Use full-text search for word matching
SELECT * FROM users WHERE to_tsvector('english', name) @@ to_tsquery('John');
```

The trigram index is often the best solution for arbitrary substring search. It supports `LIKE`, `ILIKE`, `~` (regex), and `%` (similarity) operators.

The containment operator `@>` uses a GIN index, but extracting fields with `->` or `->>` requires a B-tree expression index.

```sql
-- Create GIN index on JSONB column
CREATE INDEX idx_data ON events USING gin (data);

-- USES the GIN index (containment query)
SELECT * FROM events WHERE data @> '{"type": "click"}';
SELECT * FROM events WHERE data @> '{"user": {"role": "admin"}}';

-- DOES NOT use the GIN index (extraction)
SELECT * FROM events WHERE data->>'type' = 'click';  -- seq scan!
SELECT * FROM events WHERE data->'user'->>'role' = 'admin';  -- seq scan!

-- Fix: create B-tree expression index for specific fields
CREATE INDEX idx_events_type ON events ((data->>'type'));
CREATE INDEX idx_events_role ON events ((data->'user'->>'role'));

-- Now extraction queries use the index
SELECT * FROM events WHERE data->>'type' = 'click';  -- index scan

-- Or use jsonb_path_ops for smaller, faster containment-only index
CREATE INDEX idx_data_path ON events USING gin (data jsonb_path_ops);
-- 2-3x smaller than default gin, but only supports @> operator
```

Rule of thumb: use GIN with `@>` for flexible queries, expression indexes for frequently filtered specific fields.

Computing `to_tsvector()` on every query is slow. For production, store and index the tsvector in a dedicated column.

```sql
-- SLOW: computes tsvector on every query
SELECT * FROM articles
WHERE to_tsvector('english', title || ' ' || body) @@ to_tsquery('database & tuning');

-- FAST: pre-computed tsvector column with GIN index
ALTER TABLE articles ADD COLUMN search_vector tsvector;

UPDATE articles SET search_vector =
    setweight(to_tsvector('english', coalesce(title, '')), 'A') ||
    setweight(to_tsvector('english', coalesce(body, '')), 'B');

CREATE INDEX idx_articles_search ON articles USING gin (search_vector);

-- Auto-update with trigger
CREATE FUNCTION articles_search_update() RETURNS trigger AS $$
BEGIN
    NEW.search_vector :=
        setweight(to_tsvector('english', coalesce(NEW.title, '')), 'A') ||
        setweight(to_tsvector('english', coalesce(NEW.body, '')), 'B');
    RETURN NEW;
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;

CREATE TRIGGER trg_articles_search
    BEFORE INSERT OR UPDATE OF title, body ON articles
    FOR EACH ROW EXECUTE FUNCTION articles_search_update();

-- Query with ranking
SELECT title, ts_rank(search_vector, query) AS rank
FROM articles, to_tsquery('english', 'database & tuning') query
WHERE search_vector @@ query
ORDER BY rank DESC
LIMIT 20;
```

The `setweight` function lets you weight title matches higher than body matches. Weights go from A (highest) to D (lowest).

PostgreSQL's default isolation level (READ COMMITTED) means a long-running transaction can see different data if another transaction commits during its execution.

```sql
-- Session A (READ COMMITTED — default)
BEGIN;
SELECT balance FROM accounts WHERE id = 1;  -- returns 1000

-- Session B commits: UPDATE accounts SET balance = 500 WHERE id = 1;

SELECT balance FROM accounts WHERE id = 1;  -- returns 500! Different!
COMMIT;

-- Fix: use REPEATABLE READ for consistent snapshots
BEGIN ISOLATION LEVEL REPEATABLE READ;
SELECT balance FROM accounts WHERE id = 1;  -- returns 1000

-- Session B commits: UPDATE accounts SET balance = 500 WHERE id = 1;

SELECT balance FROM accounts WHERE id = 1;  -- still returns 1000!
COMMIT;

-- SERIALIZABLE for full consistency (at performance cost)
BEGIN ISOLATION LEVEL SERIALIZABLE;
-- All transactions appear to execute sequentially
-- May get serialization failures that require retry
COMMIT;
```

For reporting queries or analytics that need a consistent snapshot, always use `REPEATABLE READ`. For financial calculations, consider `SERIALIZABLE` with retry logic.

Two transactions updating the same rows in different order will deadlock. PostgreSQL detects this and kills one transaction.

```sql
-- Session A:
BEGIN;
UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance - 100 WHERE id = 1;  -- locks row 1
UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance + 100 WHERE id = 2;  -- waits for B

-- Session B:
BEGIN;
UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance - 50 WHERE id = 2;   -- locks row 2
UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance + 50 WHERE id = 1;   -- waits for A
-- DEADLOCK DETECTED!

-- Fix: always lock rows in consistent order
BEGIN;
-- Sort IDs and lock in order
SELECT * FROM accounts WHERE id IN (1, 2) ORDER BY id FOR UPDATE;
-- Now update in any order safely
UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance - 100 WHERE id = 1;
UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance + 100 WHERE id = 2;
COMMIT;

-- Alternative: use advisory locks
SELECT pg_advisory_xact_lock(hashtext('transfer'), LEAST(1,2), GREATEST(1,2));
```

```sql
-- Monitor deadlocks
SELECT deadlocks FROM pg_stat_database WHERE datname = current_database();

-- Log deadlocks (postgresql.conf)
-- log_lock_waits = on
-- deadlock_timeout = 1s
```

By default, table owners and superusers bypass all RLS policies. You must explicitly force RLS on owners if needed.

```sql
-- Enable RLS
ALTER TABLE documents ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY;

-- Create policy
CREATE POLICY user_documents ON documents
    USING (user_id = current_setting('app.current_user_id')::int);

-- GOTCHA: table owner bypasses this!
SET ROLE table_owner;
SELECT * FROM documents;  -- returns ALL rows!

-- Force RLS on owner too
ALTER TABLE documents FORCE ROW LEVEL SECURITY;

-- Now even the owner is subject to policies
-- But superusers ALWAYS bypass RLS

-- Common pattern: separate app role from owner
CREATE ROLE app_user;
GRANT SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE ON documents TO app_user;

-- Set user context from application
SET LOCAL app.current_user_id = '123';
SELECT * FROM documents;  -- only user 123's docs

-- Policy for multi-tenant apps
CREATE POLICY tenant_isolation ON orders
    USING (tenant_id = current_setting('app.tenant_id')::int)
    WITH CHECK (tenant_id = current_setting('app.tenant_id')::int);
```

The `WITH CHECK` clause applies to INSERT and UPDATE — it ensures new/modified rows also satisfy the policy.

PostgreSQL triggers default to `FOR EACH STATEMENT`, which fires once even if the operation affects multiple rows. Most people want `FOR EACH ROW`.

```sql
-- WRONG: fires once for entire INSERT batch
CREATE TRIGGER log_insert
    AFTER INSERT ON orders
    -- missing FOR EACH ROW!
    EXECUTE FUNCTION log_change();

-- Inserting 1000 rows fires trigger ONCE, not 1000 times
INSERT INTO orders SELECT ... FROM generate_series(1, 1000);

-- CORRECT: fires for each row
CREATE TRIGGER log_insert
    AFTER INSERT ON orders
    FOR EACH ROW
    EXECUTE FUNCTION log_change();

-- Trigger function with access to old/new rows
CREATE FUNCTION log_change() RETURNS trigger AS $$
BEGIN
    IF TG_OP = 'INSERT' THEN
        INSERT INTO audit_log (table_name, action, new_data)
        VALUES (TG_TABLE_NAME, 'INSERT', row_to_json(NEW));
    ELSIF TG_OP = 'UPDATE' THEN
        INSERT INTO audit_log (table_name, action, old_data, new_data)
        VALUES (TG_TABLE_NAME, 'UPDATE', row_to_json(OLD), row_to_json(NEW));
    ELSIF TG_OP = 'DELETE' THEN
        INSERT INTO audit_log (table_name, action, old_data)
        VALUES (TG_TABLE_NAME, 'DELETE', row_to_json(OLD));
    END IF;
    RETURN NEW;
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;
```

`FOR EACH STATEMENT` triggers don't have access to `NEW` or `OLD` row variables. They're useful for logging statement-level events.

Before PostgreSQL 11, adding a column with a DEFAULT rewrites the entire table with an ACCESS EXCLUSIVE lock. In 11+, this is instant for most types.

```sql
-- PostgreSQL 11+: INSTANT (no table rewrite)
ALTER TABLE users ADD COLUMN is_verified boolean DEFAULT false;
ALTER TABLE users ADD COLUMN created_at timestamptz DEFAULT now();

-- Still SLOW (requires table rewrite) even in 11+:
ALTER TABLE users ADD COLUMN data jsonb DEFAULT '{}'::jsonb;  -- volatile!
ALTER TABLE users ADD COLUMN score int DEFAULT random();       -- volatile!

-- To check if a default is volatile:
-- If DEFAULT expression is VOLATILE, it requires a table rewrite

-- Safe migration patterns for zero-downtime:
-- 1. Add column without default (instant)
ALTER TABLE users ADD COLUMN new_col text;
-- 2. Set default for new rows
ALTER TABLE users ALTER COLUMN new_col SET DEFAULT 'value';
-- 3. Backfill in batches
UPDATE users SET new_col = 'value' WHERE id BETWEEN 1 AND 10000;
UPDATE users SET new_col = 'value' WHERE id BETWEEN 10001 AND 20000;
-- 4. Add NOT NULL constraint with validation
ALTER TABLE users ADD CONSTRAINT users_new_col_nn CHECK (new_col IS NOT NULL) NOT VALID;
ALTER TABLE users VALIDATE CONSTRAINT users_new_col_nn;
```

A regular `CREATE INDEX` takes a write lock on the table. For large tables, this can block inserts and updates for minutes or hours.

```sql
-- BLOCKS writes during entire index build!
CREATE INDEX idx_users_email ON users (email);

-- Non-blocking: CONCURRENTLY
CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY idx_users_email ON users (email);

-- Caveats of CONCURRENTLY:
-- 1. Takes 2-3x longer
-- 2. Cannot run inside a transaction
-- 3. If it fails, leaves an INVALID index
SELECT indexrelid::regclass, indisvalid
FROM pg_index
WHERE NOT indisvalid;  -- check for invalid indexes

-- Clean up invalid index
DROP INDEX CONCURRENTLY idx_users_email;
CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY idx_users_email ON users (email);

-- Same for REINDEX
REINDEX INDEX CONCURRENTLY idx_users_email;

-- DROP INDEX also blocks — use CONCURRENTLY
DROP INDEX CONCURRENTLY idx_users_email;

-- Unique constraint via concurrent index
CREATE UNIQUE INDEX CONCURRENTLY idx_users_email_uniq ON users (email);
ALTER TABLE users ADD CONSTRAINT users_email_unique USING INDEX idx_users_email_uniq;
```

Always use `CONCURRENTLY` in production. The slight performance penalty is worth avoiding downtime.

The `SERIAL` pseudo-type has subtle issues with permissions, ownership, and replication. The SQL-standard `GENERATED ALWAYS AS IDENTITY` is the modern replacement.

```sql
-- OLD: SERIAL (not recommended)
CREATE TABLE users (
    id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY  -- creates a sequence with specific permissions
);
-- Issues: sequence is separate object, permission problems, INSERT can override
INSERT INTO users (id) VALUES (999);  -- allowed! breaks sequence

-- NEW: IDENTITY (recommended, PostgreSQL 10+)
CREATE TABLE users (
    id int GENERATED ALWAYS AS IDENTITY PRIMARY KEY
);
-- INSERT INTO users (id) VALUES (999);  -- ERROR!
-- Must explicitly override:
INSERT INTO users (id) OVERRIDING SYSTEM VALUE VALUES (999);

-- GENERATED BY DEFAULT: allows manual values (like SERIAL behavior)
CREATE TABLE events (
    id bigint GENERATED BY DEFAULT AS IDENTITY PRIMARY KEY
);
INSERT INTO events (id) VALUES (999);  -- allowed

-- Migrate from SERIAL to IDENTITY
ALTER TABLE users
    ALTER COLUMN id DROP DEFAULT,
    ALTER COLUMN id ADD GENERATED ALWAYS AS IDENTITY;
SELECT setval(pg_get_serial_sequence('users', 'id'), MAX(id)) FROM users;
```

Use `bigint GENERATED ALWAYS AS IDENTITY` for new tables. The `ALWAYS` variant prevents accidental manual ID assignment.

Unlike MySQL with MyISAM, PostgreSQL doesn't store a row count cache. `COUNT(*)` on a large table requires a full table scan due to MVCC.

```sql
-- SLOW on large tables (full table scan)
SELECT COUNT(*) FROM events;  -- scans every row

-- Fast estimate from stats (±5-10% accurate)
SELECT reltuples::bigint AS estimate
FROM pg_class
WHERE relname = 'events';

-- More accurate estimate after ANALYZE
ANALYZE events;
SELECT reltuples::bigint FROM pg_class WHERE relname = 'events';

-- Fast exact count for filtered queries with index
SELECT COUNT(*) FROM events WHERE status = 'active';
-- Uses index-only scan if status is indexed and table is vacuumed

-- Materialized counter for exact counts
CREATE TABLE counters (table_name text PRIMARY KEY, row_count bigint);

CREATE FUNCTION update_event_count() RETURNS trigger AS $$
BEGIN
    IF TG_OP = 'INSERT' THEN
        UPDATE counters SET row_count = row_count + 1 WHERE table_name = 'events';
    ELSIF TG_OP = 'DELETE' THEN
        UPDATE counters SET row_count = row_count - 1 WHERE table_name = 'events';
    END IF;
    RETURN NULL;
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;

CREATE TRIGGER trg_event_count AFTER INSERT OR DELETE ON events
FOR EACH ROW EXECUTE FUNCTION update_event_count();
```

The trigger-based counter adds overhead to writes but gives O(1) count queries. Use `pg_class.reltuples` for dashboards that don't need exact counts.

Foreign keys referencing a partitioned table require the referenced columns to be part of the partition key. Detaching/attaching partitions also requires careful handling.

```sql
-- This FAILS:
CREATE TABLE orders (
    id bigint GENERATED ALWAYS AS IDENTITY,
    created_at date NOT NULL
) PARTITION BY RANGE (created_at);

CREATE TABLE order_items (
    order_id bigint REFERENCES orders(id)  -- ERROR!
);
-- ERROR: foreign key must include partition key columns

-- Fix: include partition key in the reference
CREATE TABLE orders (
    id bigint NOT NULL,
    created_at date NOT NULL,
    PRIMARY KEY (id, created_at)  -- partition key must be in PK
) PARTITION BY RANGE (created_at);

-- Detach partition concurrently (14+)
ALTER TABLE orders DETACH PARTITION orders_2023_01 CONCURRENTLY;
-- Without CONCURRENTLY, this takes ACCESS EXCLUSIVE lock on parent!

-- Attach requires validation (can be slow)
ALTER TABLE orders ATTACH PARTITION orders_2024_03
    FOR VALUES FROM ('2024-03-01') TO ('2024-04-01');
-- Scans the partition to validate constraint — use large maintenance_work_mem
```

The partition key requirement for foreign keys is the biggest ergonomic issue with PostgreSQL partitioning. Consider application-level referential integrity for partitioned tables.

Adding `NOT NULL` to an existing column requires PostgreSQL to scan every row to verify no NULLs exist. On large tables, this means long lock times.

```sql
-- SLOW: full table scan with ACCESS EXCLUSIVE lock
ALTER TABLE users ALTER COLUMN email SET NOT NULL;

-- FAST zero-downtime approach (PostgreSQL 12+):
-- 1. Add constraint NOT VALID (no scan, quick lock)
ALTER TABLE users ADD CONSTRAINT users_email_nn
    CHECK (email IS NOT NULL) NOT VALID;

-- 2. Validate in background (SHARE UPDATE EXCLUSIVE lock, allows reads+writes)
ALTER TABLE users VALIDATE CONSTRAINT users_email_nn;

-- 3. Now add the real NOT NULL (recognizes the existing constraint, no scan)
ALTER TABLE users ALTER COLUMN email SET NOT NULL;

-- 4. Clean up the redundant constraint
ALTER TABLE users DROP CONSTRAINT users_email_nn;

-- Same pattern for foreign keys:
ALTER TABLE orders ADD CONSTRAINT fk_user
    FOREIGN KEY (user_id) REFERENCES users(id) NOT VALID;
ALTER TABLE orders VALIDATE CONSTRAINT fk_user;
```

This three-step pattern is the standard for zero-downtime constraint additions on large PostgreSQL tables.

PostgreSQL's deadlock detector identifies circular lock dependencies and kills one of the transactions. The killed transaction must be retried.

```
ERROR: deadlock detected
DETAIL: Process 1234 waits for ShareLock on transaction 5678;
  blocked by process 5678.
  Process 5678 waits for ShareLock on transaction 1234;
  blocked by process 1234.
HINT: See server log for query details.
```

```sql
-- Common cause: concurrent updates in different order
-- Session A: UPDATE accounts SET x=1 WHERE id=1; UPDATE accounts SET x=1 WHERE id=2;
-- Session B: UPDATE accounts SET x=1 WHERE id=2; UPDATE accounts SET x=1 WHERE id=1;

-- Fix 1: always lock in consistent order
SELECT * FROM accounts WHERE id IN (1, 2) ORDER BY id FOR UPDATE;

-- Fix 2: use SKIP LOCKED for queue-like patterns
SELECT * FROM tasks
WHERE status = 'pending'
ORDER BY created_at
LIMIT 1
FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED;  -- skip locked rows instead of waiting

-- Monitor deadlocks
SELECT deadlocks FROM pg_stat_database WHERE datname = current_database();
```

```python
# Application retry pattern
async def with_retry(func, max_retries=3):
    for attempt in range(max_retries):
        try:
            return await func()
        except asyncpg.DeadlockDetectedError:
            if attempt == max_retries - 1:
                raise
            await asyncio.sleep(random.uniform(0.01, 0.1 * (2 ** attempt)))
```

PostgreSQL has fine-grained permissions. Creating a table doesn't automatically grant access to other roles.

```
ERROR: permission denied for table users
```

```sql
-- Grant specific privileges
GRANT SELECT ON users TO app_readonly;
GRANT SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE ON users TO app_readwrite;
GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON users TO app_admin;

-- Grant on all tables in schema
GRANT SELECT ON ALL TABLES IN SCHEMA public TO app_readonly;

-- Grant for future tables too (crucial!)
ALTER DEFAULT PRIVILEGES IN SCHEMA public
    GRANT SELECT ON TABLES TO app_readonly;
ALTER DEFAULT PRIVILEGES IN SCHEMA public
    GRANT SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE ON TABLES TO app_readwrite;

-- Don't forget sequence permissions for INSERT
GRANT USAGE ON ALL SEQUENCES IN SCHEMA public TO app_readwrite;
ALTER DEFAULT PRIVILEGES IN SCHEMA public
    GRANT USAGE ON SEQUENCES TO app_readwrite;

-- Check current grants
SELECT grantee, privilege_type
FROM information_schema.role_table_grants
WHERE table_name = 'users';

-- Check role memberships
SELECT r.rolname AS role, m.rolname AS member
FROM pg_auth_members am
JOIN pg_roles r ON am.roleid = r.oid
JOIN pg_roles m ON am.member = m.oid;
```

The most common mistake is forgetting `ALTER DEFAULT PRIVILEGES` — without it, new tables created later won't have the grants.

A checklist of safe vs dangerous migration operations in PostgreSQL, with the safe alternatives.

```sql
-- DANGEROUS → SAFE alternatives:

-- 1. ADD COLUMN with NOT NULL
-- Dangerous: ALTER TABLE t ADD COLUMN c text NOT NULL DEFAULT 'x';
-- Safe (PG 11+): Same command is instant for non-volatile defaults
-- Safe (PG <11):
ALTER TABLE t ADD COLUMN c text;
ALTER TABLE t ALTER COLUMN c SET DEFAULT 'x';
-- backfill in batches
ALTER TABLE t ADD CONSTRAINT c_nn CHECK (c IS NOT NULL) NOT VALID;
ALTER TABLE t VALIDATE CONSTRAINT c_nn;

-- 2. ADD INDEX
-- Dangerous: CREATE INDEX idx ON t (col);  -- blocks writes
-- Safe:
CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY idx ON t (col);

-- 3. ADD FOREIGN KEY
-- Dangerous: ALTER TABLE t ADD FOREIGN KEY (col) REFERENCES other(id);
-- Safe:
ALTER TABLE t ADD CONSTRAINT fk FOREIGN KEY (col) REFERENCES other(id) NOT VALID;
ALTER TABLE t VALIDATE CONSTRAINT fk;

-- 4. CHANGE COLUMN TYPE
-- Dangerous: ALTER TABLE t ALTER COLUMN c TYPE bigint;  -- rewrites table
-- Safe: add new column, backfill, swap
ALTER TABLE t ADD COLUMN c_new bigint;
-- backfill c_new from c in batches
-- update application to write both columns
-- swap columns:
ALTER TABLE t RENAME COLUMN c TO c_old;
ALTER TABLE t RENAME COLUMN c_new TO c;

-- 5. SET lock_timeout for all DDL
SET LOCAL lock_timeout = '3s';
-- Retry if timeout — prevents blocking cascades

-- 6. RENAME TABLE (use a view for transition)
ALTER TABLE old_name RENAME TO new_name;
CREATE VIEW old_name AS SELECT * FROM new_name;
```

For processing large result sets without loading everything into memory, use cursor-based (keyset) pagination.

```sql
-- WRONG: OFFSET pagination (gets slower for large offsets)
SELECT * FROM events ORDER BY id LIMIT 1000 OFFSET 1000000;
-- PostgreSQL must scan and discard 1M rows!

-- CORRECT: Keyset pagination (constant time for any page)
SELECT * FROM events
WHERE id > 1000000  -- last seen ID
ORDER BY id
LIMIT 1000;
-- Uses index, always fast

-- For compound sort keys
SELECT * FROM events
WHERE (created_at, id) > ('2024-01-15 10:00:00', 12345)
ORDER BY created_at, id
LIMIT 1000;
-- Requires index: CREATE INDEX ON events (created_at, id)

-- Batch UPDATE pattern
DO $$
DECLARE
    batch_size int := 1000;
    rows_updated int;
    last_id bigint := 0;
BEGIN
    LOOP
        UPDATE events SET processed = true
        WHERE id IN (
            SELECT id FROM events
            WHERE id > last_id AND processed = false
            ORDER BY id LIMIT batch_size
            FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED
        )
        RETURNING max(id) INTO last_id;

        GET DIAGNOSTICS rows_updated = ROW_COUNT;
        EXIT WHEN rows_updated = 0;

        COMMIT;  -- release locks between batches (PG 11+ procedure)
        RAISE NOTICE 'Updated % rows, last_id=%', rows_updated, last_id;
    END LOOP;
END;
$$;
```

Partition time-series data by date range with automatic partition creation using pg_partman or manual approach.

```sql
-- Create partitioned table
CREATE TABLE metrics (
    id bigint GENERATED ALWAYS AS IDENTITY,
    name text NOT NULL,
    value double precision NOT NULL,
    recorded_at timestamptz NOT NULL
) PARTITION BY RANGE (recorded_at);

-- Create partitions
CREATE TABLE metrics_2024_01 PARTITION OF metrics
    FOR VALUES FROM ('2024-01-01') TO ('2024-02-01');
CREATE TABLE metrics_2024_02 PARTITION OF metrics
    FOR VALUES FROM ('2024-02-01') TO ('2024-03-01');

-- Create default partition for overflow
CREATE TABLE metrics_default PARTITION OF metrics DEFAULT;

-- Auto-create partitions with pg_partman
CREATE EXTENSION pg_partman;
SELECT partman.create_parent(
    p_parent_table := 'public.metrics',
    p_control := 'recorded_at',
    p_type := 'native',
    p_interval := 'monthly',
    p_premake := 3  -- create 3 future partitions
);

-- Schedule partition maintenance
SELECT cron.schedule('partition-maintenance', '0 1 * * *',
    $$SELECT partman.run_maintenance()$$
);

-- Drop old partitions (data retention)
ALTER TABLE metrics DETACH PARTITION metrics_2023_01 CONCURRENTLY;
DROP TABLE metrics_2023_01;  -- instant, no VACUUM needed

-- Partition-specific indexes
CREATE INDEX ON metrics (name, recorded_at);
-- Automatically created on each partition
```

Partitioning shines when you need efficient data retention (drop partition vs DELETE + VACUUM) and time-range queries.

Track all changes to a table using a history table and triggers, supporting point-in-time queries.

```sql
-- Main table
CREATE TABLE products (
    id int PRIMARY KEY,
    name text NOT NULL,
    price numeric NOT NULL,
    updated_at timestamptz NOT NULL DEFAULT now()
);

-- History table (same structure + audit columns)
CREATE TABLE products_history (
    history_id bigint GENERATED ALWAYS AS IDENTITY PRIMARY KEY,
    id int NOT NULL,
    name text NOT NULL,
    price numeric NOT NULL,
    updated_at timestamptz NOT NULL,
    valid_from timestamptz NOT NULL,
    valid_to timestamptz NOT NULL DEFAULT 'infinity',
    operation char(1) NOT NULL  -- I/U/D
);

CREATE INDEX idx_products_history ON products_history (id, valid_from, valid_to);

-- Trigger function
CREATE FUNCTION track_product_changes() RETURNS trigger AS $$
BEGIN
    IF TG_OP = 'UPDATE' OR TG_OP = 'DELETE' THEN
        UPDATE products_history SET valid_to = now()
        WHERE id = OLD.id AND valid_to = 'infinity';
    END IF;

    IF TG_OP = 'INSERT' OR TG_OP = 'UPDATE' THEN
        INSERT INTO products_history (id, name, price, updated_at, valid_from, operation)
        VALUES (NEW.id, NEW.name, NEW.price, NEW.updated_at, now(), left(TG_OP, 1));
    END IF;

    IF TG_OP = 'DELETE' THEN
        INSERT INTO products_history (id, name, price, updated_at, valid_from, valid_to, operation)
        VALUES (OLD.id, OLD.name, OLD.price, OLD.updated_at, now(), now(), 'D');
    END IF;

    RETURN COALESCE(NEW, OLD);
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;

CREATE TRIGGER trg_products_audit
    AFTER INSERT OR UPDATE OR DELETE ON products
    FOR EACH ROW EXECUTE FUNCTION track_product_changes();

-- Point-in-time query
SELECT * FROM products_history
WHERE id = 1
  AND valid_from <= '2024-01-15 10:00:00'
  AND valid_to > '2024-01-15 10:00:00';
```

A safe migration script template with timeouts, transaction management, and rollback support.

```sql
-- Migration: add user_preferences table and status column
-- Author: team
-- Date: 2024-01-15

-- Safety guards
SET lock_timeout = '3s';
SET statement_timeout = '300s';

-- Pre-flight check
DO $$
BEGIN
    IF EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM pg_tables WHERE tablename = 'user_preferences') THEN
        RAISE EXCEPTION 'Migration already applied: user_preferences table exists';
    END IF;
END;
$$;

-- Step 1: Create new table (no lock on existing tables)
CREATE TABLE user_preferences (
    user_id int PRIMARY KEY REFERENCES users(id),
    theme text NOT NULL DEFAULT 'light',
    language text NOT NULL DEFAULT 'en',
    notifications jsonb NOT NULL DEFAULT '{"email": true, "push": true}',
    created_at timestamptz NOT NULL DEFAULT now(),
    updated_at timestamptz NOT NULL DEFAULT now()
);

-- Step 2: Add column (instant in PG 11+ with non-volatile default)
ALTER TABLE users ADD COLUMN status text NOT NULL DEFAULT 'active';

-- Step 3: Create index concurrently (non-blocking)
CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY idx_users_status ON users (status);

-- Step 4: Add constraint NOT VALID then validate (non-blocking)
ALTER TABLE users ADD CONSTRAINT valid_status
    CHECK (status IN ('active', 'inactive', 'suspended')) NOT VALID;
ALTER TABLE users VALIDATE CONSTRAINT valid_status;

-- Step 5: Backfill in batches (for large tables)
DO $$
DECLARE
    batch_size int := 5000;
    total int;
BEGIN
    SELECT count(*) INTO total FROM users WHERE status IS NULL;
    RAISE NOTICE 'Backfilling % rows', total;

    WHILE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM users WHERE status IS NULL LIMIT 1) LOOP
        UPDATE users SET status = 'active'
        WHERE id IN (
            SELECT id FROM users WHERE status IS NULL LIMIT batch_size
        );
        RAISE NOTICE 'Batch complete';
        PERFORM pg_sleep(0.1);  -- brief pause between batches
    END LOOP;
END;
$$;

-- Rollback script (save separately)
-- DROP INDEX CONCURRENTLY IF EXISTS idx_users_status;
-- ALTER TABLE users DROP CONSTRAINT IF EXISTS valid_status;
-- ALTER TABLE users DROP COLUMN IF EXISTS status;
